d other silly stuff coming soon!','Edinburgh 2012!','','inherit','open','open','','174314-revision-7','','','2012-08-03 01:17:30','2012-08-02 23:17:30','',174314,'http://comedyinenglish.de/2012/08/03/174314-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(272479,5,'2012-08-04 11:31:09','2012-08-04 09:31:09','','How to Improve as a Comedian','','trash','open','open','','how-to-improve-as-a-comedian-2','','','2012-09-29 18:13:15','2012-09-29 16:13:15','',0,'http://comedyinenglish.de/?p=272479',0,'post','',0),(272480,5,'2012-08-04 11:45:58','2012-08-04 09:45:58','<a href=\"http://comedyinenglish.de/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/evolve.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-272503\" src=\"http://comedyinenglish.de/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/evolve.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"413\" height=\"192\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<em>By Paul Salamone, host of <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pages/Comedy-in-SIN/170898937628\">Comedy in SIN</a></em>\r\n\r\nYou want to get better at doing stand-up comedy? Below are ten general principles, gleaned from both personal experience and public statements made by professionals, that have helped me grow as a writer and performer ever since I started doing stand-up in 2009. They might work for you, they might be bullshit. Feel free to add your own in the comments section below.\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Perform as much as possible, wherever possible.\r\n</strong>Many <a href=\"http://glasgowphillips.blogspot.de/2007/02/patton-oswalt-interview.html\">top comedians</a> have the same advice for comics starting out: stage time, stage time, stage time. If you\'re lucky enough to live in a city with a strong open mic scene, you have no excuse not to hit that up. If not, move to a city that does have one, or start your own. If you can\'t even do that, take the advice of Zach Galifinakis pal <a href=\"http://www.jimmydorecomedy.com/comedy-and-everything-else/episode-135-with-brody-stevens\">Brody Stevens</a> and grab any sort of public-speaking gig you can get your hands on. Tour guide, carneval barker, karaoke DJ -- whatever puts you in front of a crowd with a microphone can help you build confidence and learn that subtle balance of sensitivity and not giving a shit which is the comedian\'s calling card.\r\n\r\nAnd if that doesn\'t inspire you, maybe this will: my friend Mateusz used to drive 2 hours every Tuesday night from Stettin, Poland to Berlin to do a 5-minute set at an open mic I hosted in a tiny bar. Why did he stop? Because he got enough confidence to <a href=\"http://www.wszczecinie.pl/aktualnosci,mikrofon_bedzie_twoj-mind_open_mic,id-20177.html\">start his own night</a>, in Poland. I hope to be going there soon.\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong><strong>2. Be patient.</strong>\r\nIn <em><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outliers_(book)\">Outliers</a></em>, Malcolm Gladwell talks about something called \"the Mozart effect\" which states that mastery of any craft requires 10,000 hours of practice. Similarly, comedy duo <a href=\"http://www.earwolf.com/show/sklarbro-country/\">The Sklar Brothers</a> say it takes about 8 years to \"break through\" in comedy. If you\'re serious about it, face the fact you\'re in it for the long haul, and no one becomes successful overnight. Keep your head down, focus on the craft, rack up your stage time, and don\'t worry so much about marketing yourself on the internet until you\'ve got something outstanding to show. (There are enough terrible videos of me half-assing it online to know this from a deep personal level). <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HHSaQ7ODBag\">Dane Cook</a> famously made it big via clever use of MySpace, but this was backed up by years of hard work in the clubs of Boston and NYC. Speaking of which, you probably don\'t need to move to a big town just yet -- as Conan O\'Brien warm-up comedian and podcaster <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OjuNLjXM4Tk\">Jimmy Pardo</a> says, you need to \"get your ass kicked in Nebraska\" before it\'s time to move to the big time. (Then again, what the fuck do I know, I live in a city filled with people like <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=58PAu-WGB7g&amp;feature=player_embedded#!\">this</a>.)\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold\">3.  Always have a notebook handy.\r\n</span>Look, it\'s so easy: keep a notebook in your back pocket...or in your purse, or on your iPhone, or on your hand. I have learned the hard way not to take funny ideas for granted, and am never more than a step away from a notebook or a voice recorder to capture ANYTHING that I might think is funny. This doesn\'t mean that everything is funny, let alone that any of it will end up as a successful joke on stage, but it does get you in the habit of being aware of your thougths and your surroundings, and being able to put into words. And when something truly funny does occur to you, you\'ll be ready.\r\n\r\nWoody Allen, in an interview with <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Woody-Allen-on-Comedy-Explicit/dp/B000S5E1RK/ref=sr_1_13?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1334615357&amp;sr=8-13\">Laugh.com</a>, described his stand-up comedy writing process thusly (I\'m paraphrasing): he would constantly takes notes on little pieces of paper, napkins, etc. and put them in a drawer. Whenever he has to come up with a new piece, he\'d get all the notes out and try to fit them into a coherent story of 20 minutes or so in length which he\'d type out. Then he\'d cut that down to about 8 minutes, perform it, and cut that down to another 5. Lots of work, lots of notes.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Write jokes every day.\r\n</strong>In <a href=\"http://yea.fm/album/280-Comedy___Spoken_Word/74996-Jerry_Seinfeld_On_Comedy/#/album/280-Comedy___Spoken_Word/74996-Jerry_Seinfeld_On_Comedy/\">\"Jerry Seinfeld on Comedy\"</a> (a great interview everyone should listen to), Seinfeld, a notorious workaholic, talks about how he would write jokes every day for an hour. Comedy Central Roast star <a href=\"http://www.nerdist.com/2011/08/making-it-6-anthony-jeselnik/\">Anthony Jeselnik</a> does it for two or more. Is that enough reason? If not, this quote from This American Life\'s <a href=\"http://www.wesleyverhoeve.com/iraglass/\">Ira Glass</a>, though not from a comedian, applies regardless:\r\n<blockquote>For the first couple years you make stuff, it’s just not that good. It’s trying to be good, it has potential, but it’s not. But your taste, the thing that got you into the game, is still killer. And your taste is why your work disappoints you. A lot of people never get past this phase, they quit. Most people I know who do interesting, creative work went through years of this. We know our work doesn’t have this special thing that we want it to have. We all go through this. And if you are just starting out or you are still in this phase, you gotta know its normal and the most important thing you can do is do a lot of work.</blockquote>\r\n<strong>5. Write for the specific situation that is a live comedy show.\r\n</strong>Knowing you who are , what you\'re doing their, what your point is, why you\'re talking to people, etc. is a good exercise. My German slam poetry friend <a href=\"http://www.tillreiners.de/\">Till Reiners</a> -- who kills at every show I\'ve seen him in -- told me last week that the main way he writes his  5-minute slam texts (which are funny stories, more or less) is by standing in the middle of a crowd during a slam show and getting a feeling for what he as an <em>audience member </em>would find worth his time to listen to.  <a href=\"http://londonist.com/2008/03/dont_ever_heckl.php\">Gerry Howell</a>, an up-and-coming act in London, actually writes his jokes right after a gig, when his brain is fresh from the specific stage situation.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>6. Record your sets and learn from them.\r\n</strong> This <a href=\"http://www.amazon.de/Sony-ICDBX112-Digitale-Rekorder-silber/dp/B004SO876S\">Sony IC Recorder</a> (pictured) costs &lt;39€ and holds 2 GB (so, 500 hours?) of recording time. If you press \"record\" before you get onstage and put it in your pocket, you will get a good enough a recording that you can listen to after the show to learn what speficially people laughed at, what they didn\'t laugh at, and what new jokes you came up with on the spot that you could use next time you perform that routine. You don\'t need to upload it to your laptop, or share it online, or burn it to a CD and sell to your friends. Just use it as a tool. Learn. (I can\'t remember which podcast it was, but I\'ve heard that even <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R37zkizucPU&amp;feature=related\">Louis CK</a> records every set he does in a similar way. I mention this because very few comedians I know take advantage of this very simple technology which could benefit them greatly. IT\'S SO EASY.)\r\n\r\n<strong>7. Listen to comedy </strong><strong>as much comedy as possible.\r\n</strong>This seems like a no-brainer, but I know a lot of would-be comedians whose knowledge of the current comedy climate goes about as far as <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Hicks\">Bill Hicks</a>, who died in 1994. There\'s been a lot of brilliant comedy since then, a lot of it already tackling issues that many newbie comedians consider to be cutting-edge. With so many comedy nerds trolling the internet at present for instances of hack comedy or joke theft, you can\'t afford to \"accidentally\" do the same joke as someone more famous than you did ten years ago. Do yourself a favor and download something like <a href=\"http://www.spotify.com/\">Spotify</a>, check out the latest <a href=\"http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-best-comedy-albums-of-2011,66251/\">A/V Club</a> or <a href=\"http://www.dead-frog.com/charts\">Dead Frog</a> rankings, and hear what people TODAY think is funny. As a bonus, listening to comedy all day also builds the neurons in your brain to think like a comedian: the timing, the patter, the rhythms, the back-and-forth with the audience.\r\n\r\n<strong>8. Host your own show.</strong>\r\nNot only does hosting your own show, whether it\'s a weekly open mic, a monthly showcase, or an occasional special event, guarantee you stage time, it also shows you what it\'s like to work with comedians from a booker\'s perspective. This in turn helps you become more professional as a performer in other peoples\' shows, as you learn to do the things that make a booker\'s job easier, i.e. get to the gig on time, not go over your allotted stage time, deliver a consistent performance, not tell a hundred Holocaust jokes in a room full of old people, etc. Also, when you\'re responsible for a show that people are paying money to see, it forces you to up your own game.\r\n\r\n<strong>9. Help others get better.\r\n</strong>Not everyone needs your help, or deserves it. But some people are serious about comedy, but just need stage time, host training, or perspective on their set to take it to the next level. While I don\'t think anyone should offer specific advice (don\'t write my jokes for me, thanks), mutual support can help the whole scene grow. You can also learn how to improve your own act by watching how your peers can overcome struggles in theirs, and vice versa.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold\">10. Have a life.\r\n</span>Sometimes you\'ve got to get the hell away from the world of bars, booze, and <em><a href=\"http://www.dict.cc/deutsch-englisch/B%C3%BChnen.html\">Bühnen</a></em>. Hanging out in a comedy club too much makes you think that everyone cares about drinking, groupies, and regular patrons of said club. This is the self-referential comedy scene feedback loop from hell, and the only way out of it is to get out and do something else. Some of my best bits have come out of putting myself in very strange situations, i.e. going to a Gerhard Richter exhibition, watching the May Day riots, hanging out in Israel etc.\r\n\r\nNone of those, by the way, would have been possible to write about had I just lived in NYC  :)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','How to Improve as a Comedian','','publish','open','open','','how-to-improve-as-a-comedian','','','2012-08-04 11:45:58','2012-08-04 09:45:58','',0,'http://comedyinenglish.de/?p=272480',0,'post','',0),(272503,5,'2012-08-04 11:38:47','2012-08-04 09:38:47','','evolve','','inherit','open','open','','evolve','','','2012-08-04 11:38:47','2012-08-04 09:38:47','',272480,'http://comedyinenglish.de/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/evolve.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(272504,5,'2012-08-04 11:39:54','2012-08-04 09:39:54','<a href=\"http://comedyinenglish.de/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/evolve.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-272503\" src=\"http://comedyinenglish.de/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/evolve.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"413\" height=\"192\" /></a>\n\n<em>By Paul Salamone, host of <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pages/Comedy-in-SIN/170898937628\">Comedy in SIN</a></em>\n\nYou want to get better at doing stand-up comedy? Below are ten general principles, gleaned from both personal experience and public statements made by professionals, that have helped me grow as a writer and performer ever since I started doing stand-up in 2009. They might work for you, they might be bullshit. Feel free to add your own in the comments section below.\n\n<strong>1. Perform as much as possible, wherever possible.\n</strong>Many <a href=\"http://glasgowphillips.blogspot.de/2007/02/patton-oswalt-interview.html\">top comedians</a> have the same advice for comics starting out: stage time, stage time, stage time. If you\'re lucky enough to live in a city with a strong open mic scene, you have no excuse not to hit that up. If not, move to a city that does have one, or start your own. If you can\'t even do that, take the advice of Zach Galifinakis pal <a href=\"http://www.jimmydorecomedy.com/comedy-and-everything-else/episode-135-with-brody-stevens\">Brody Stevens</a> and grab any sort of public-speaking gig you can get your hands on. Tour guide, carneval barker, karaoke DJ -- whatever puts you in f